The cost to my parents, both Italian immigrants, was a total of 60 cents for the weekend:  25 cents for admission and 5 cents for a candy bar.  As kids we were happy and safe, and Hollywood gave us great entertainment.  Today, the cadre of self-aggrandized actors are so disgusting that since 1997  I have been in a theater 3 times, and the 4th will be in December.to see Richard Jewel.  Thank you, Clint.  Can't wait.

text: When I was younger I had a fascination for serial killers. I read all the books about the early days of profiling and even had that 6 CD series by Robert Ressler. I found it fascinating until I realized it was a mostly bullshit. Jewel is an example of that but 2 other cases are even better.  I was listening and watching when the DC Sniper case was going on. I watched the so called News shows bring on "experts" who were just basically reading out of John Douglas or Resslers books. The so called experts would say "They are most likely young, 25 to 35, white, above average intelligence, blah blah blah." And we all know how that turned out. And the case of Wayne Williams and the Atlanta Child Murders. 29 victims and he went that long because since the kids were black everyone assumed it was Klan.   Here's why it was always bullshit. Back-in-the-day black people who might be budding serial killers usually got caught pretty quick because a black person prior to 1980s couldn't walk 10 feet outside the projects or hood without a cop up their butts. White guys on the other hand were able to actually rack up some kills because being white made movement easier. As for being young that's kind of a given since it takes power to subdue a potential victim. Also the guys they had caught were caught young unless you count the really "good ones" with the highest body counts. Like Ridgeway who began at 33 years old and may have killed as late as 52. Or Lucas who was in his 40s before he was caught. And many we probably Dont even know because they "aged out". Got too old to continue. And none of these guys were particularly smart. All they had to be were white and pick victims cops and society didn't care about.  My point is that profiling is based on skewed data. There are probably tons of black victims of black serial killers through out history we will never know about because the victims were the wrong color to appear on anyone give a fuck radar.

text: A few thoughts. 1. Richard Jewell is obviously a hero. Hundreds of people could've died that night, and he deserves all the credit for the lives he saved. 2. I've noticed in the comments that people are just going "oh wow, the media are being biased, I've never seen that before", but to those who do not listen to the mainstream media (and what I'm about to say), I say this. 3. Firstly, yes, the media can be error prone; I know they're not mistake-free gods. And yes, there is sometimes a tendency to push narratives. But pushing a narrative to the point where it destroys a man's life does not happen all the time. It can happen, but that doesn't mean that it should delegitimize everything that is published or broadcast by the media. But I still have to admit, Richard Jewell's case is a really bad worst-case scenario for when narratives get forced onto people. 4. This does still look like a good movie, though.

text: I saw this ad and it kept saying ‚ÄúDecember 13‚Äù which is on my birthday. But just watching this trailer felt like this was made for me (not like as a present but like something such as a coincidence). On my birthday, I want and have a strong need to watch this. Though my family rarely watches movies, this is something special. I don‚Äôt want to beg and waste my parents‚Äô money on something that I want because I don‚Äôt want to be a burden nor spoiled, so I‚Äôll rewatch this trailer on my birthday.    ‚ÄúWhy can‚Äôt you pay yourself?‚Äù Whenever I receive money, I never use it on anything I don‚Äôt need like toys and gift cards. I always worry for my parents since they are the ones who earn money, work hard, take care of us, and buy/make food. Sometimes I wonder if I passed away like if I committed suicide, maybe their decrease in money would slow down. Maybe they would have a better life instead of wasting it on a useless person like me who was seen like a burden and even an antisocial human. So when receiving money, I always gave it to them, even if it was $100, $50, $10- any money I had in my pockets were given to them.  Well, years have passed and I‚Äôm gradually saving up money. If I get a large amount of money one day in the future, I‚Äôd give it all to them. If one day in my life will remember this trailer, I‚Äôd find a way to buy and watch it and rethink and look back into the past.   Sorry if I sounded emotional. Please don‚Äôt take this wrong and assume I am using this video as a place for like-camping and attention. I just feel, well, thankful for this movie/trailer. Sometimes I look at certain things and look back at how it used to be. How I used to be very happy in the past. How I used to be kind to everyone. But I don‚Äôt feel like I have the ability change who I am, though I can.   I‚Äôll be adding this to my Absolute Favorites playlist. I feel thankful for this trailer. Once again, sorry if I sound as if I‚Äôm begging for attention and likes and sympathy. I‚Äôm not. I don‚Äôt really have a purpose of sharing this, but I feel like I have a need to, even though it shouldn‚Äôt. Insult me, swear at me, whatever you like. I just want to say, thank you for your time.

A veritable gestalt of hubris leads the F.B.I. to suspect Jewell and hubris leads a reporter to write a story based on faulty logic that ultimately leads to Jewell's very public excoriation.  A very thoughtful, funny (yes) and moving film.

text: Richard Jewell: A movie that goes home with his pockets empty, but with his head held high.       As a critic, I give it 8/10. One more great movie to Clint Eastwood's list. The performances of Olivia Wilde and Jon Hamm were solid, but Kathy Bates, Sam Rockwell and Paul, by God, Paul Walter Hauser were the best, they never left the script for a second, they took their roles seriously and managed to be praised by the public. Unfortunately, the movie turned out to be a box office failure that grossed just $ 43 million against a budget of $ 45 million, and that seems disrespectful to me.  Richard Jewell shows us as a guy who saved thousands of people's lives from an attack, they point out that he is guilty of planting that bomb and being considered a "false hero", when in fact HE was the hero and still is. Richard Jewell is not boring, but explosive, but in a pleasant, dramatic and emotional way.
